        "body": "This update moves the project beyond just a \"picture\" of a website and turns it into a functional tool. Here are the main things I’ve added:\r\n\r\nModular Building Blocks\r\nI broke the layout into three distinct pieces: the Sidebar, the Feed, and the Widgets. This makes the code much easier to read because each file only handles one specific part of the screen.\r\n\r\nShort-term Memory (State)\r\nI added a \"brain\" to the feed. Now, when you type a message, the app actually listens and remembers those words. When you click the Post button, it immediately adds that message to your screen without needing the page to reload.\r\n\r\nLong-term Memory (Local Storage)\r\nUsually, a website \"forgets\" everything the moment you refresh it. I connected the app to the browser's internal storage so that your posts are saved to your computer. You can close the tab, come back later, and your posts will still be there.\r\n\r\nPersonalized Identity\r\nTo make it feel like a real account, I added a simple check at the start. It asks for your name and handle, then automatically \"stamps\" that information onto every post you make.\r\n\r\nSpace Management\r\nSince browser memory isn't infinite, I added a small counter at the top. it tracks how many posts you’ve saved out of a 10-post limit, which helps keep the app running smoothly.\r\n\r\nHow to check it out:\r\nJust open the page and follow the prompt to enter your name. Try making a few posts and then refresh the browser—you'll see the app \"remembering\" who you are and what you wrote.",
